    "review::.::holistic::high_level_elegance::stats_panels_copy_specialize_pattern::07f1f458": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::high_level_elegance::stats_panels_copy_specialize_pattern::07f1f458",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "The MCP and RAG panels duplicate the same table-panel design with separate local contracts, which hides a missing shared visualization boundary.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "high_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/McpStatsPanel.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/RagStatsPanel.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/hooks/useTelemetry.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "Both panels define a local `*Stat` interface, a local color map, a local mono font constant, the same empty-state container pattern, and nearly identical `<table>` markup with row rendering.",
          "Neither panel imports a shared stat contract from a dashboard domain module; instead, each re-declares the API payload shape locally while `useTelemetry()` returns untyped `res.json()` data for both endpoints.",
          "This creates a copy-and-specialize growth path where every new stats panel will likely repeat the same structure with another local DTO and another untyped fetch function."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Introduce a shared dashboard stats-table primitive plus exported MCP/RAG read-model types near the data boundary, then let each panel provide only column definitions and domain-specific formatting.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-02T01:44:24+00:00",
