    "review::.::holistic::high_level_elegance::dashboard_styles_have_implicit_app_shell_side_effects::39d8ceb4": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::high_level_elegance::dashboard_styles_have_implicit_app_shell_side_effects::39d8ceb4",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "`dashboard.css.ts` combines reusable styles with document-level global mutations, so importing dashboard styling also changes the host app shell implicitly.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "high_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "src/dashboard/dashboard.css.ts",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/McpStatsPanel.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/RagStatsPanel.tsx"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`src/dashboard/dashboard.css.ts` executes `globalStyle('html, body', ...)` and `globalStyle('#root', ...)` at module load time in the same file that exports reusable classes like `panel`, `panelHeader`, and `panelBody`.",
          "The visualization panels currently bypass those shared panel styles and use their own inline styles, which means the module is simultaneously trying to be a global shell stylesheet and a reusable component-style library.",
          "That mixed role makes the dashboard\u2019s top-level styling boundary unclear: importing dashboard styles is not just opting into classes, it also imposes page-wide behavior through import-time side effects."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Move app-shell globals into a dedicated entry stylesheet loaded once by the dashboard root, and keep `dashboard.css.ts` focused on explicit component class exports that leaf panels can consume without also mutating document-level styling.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-02T01:44:24+00:00",
