      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "`useTelemetry` mirrors backend endpoints one function at a time, forcing consumers to orchestrate integration details instead of consuming a cohesive dashboard data boundary.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "mid_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "src/dashboard/hooks/useTelemetry.ts",
          "src/server/start.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`useTelemetry` returns more than a dozen narrowly scoped fetch callbacks (`fetchToolCalls`, `fetchLatencyStats`, `fetchEvalTimeseries`, `fetchDriftSummary`, etc.) at lines 277-307.",
          "The same hook mixes stateful concerns (`events`, `sessions`, `connected`) with raw endpoint wrappers and one-off fallback shaping (`fetchLatestBreakdown` returns `{ segments: [] }`, others return raw JSON) at lines 6-120 and 277-307.",
          "`start.ts` stays as a single-purpose process entrypoint, so the seam complexity in this batch is concentrated in the dashboard hook rather than being distributed across clear collaborators."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Refactor the hook around a smaller client boundary, for example a typed dashboard service or session-scoped query object that groups related session data and performs response normalization in one place. Expose higher-level operations such as `loadSessionDashboard(sessionId)` and `refreshDerivedViews(sessionId, eventTypes)` rather than endpoint-by-endpoint fetch wrappers.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
