    "review::.::holistic::authorization_consistency::missing_server_auth_boundary::88d66698": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::authorization_consistency::missing_server_auth_boundary::88d66698",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "The server exposes all telemetry read/write surfaces without any authentication boundary.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "authorization_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "src/server/index.ts",
          "src/server/cli.ts",
          "src/dashboard/hooks/useTelemetry.ts",
          "src/collector/index.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`src/server/index.ts` registers every API and both WebSocket endpoints with direct handlers only; there is no shared auth middleware, route-level `preHandler`, API key check, or distinction between public and privileged routes.",
          "The default CLI host in `src/server/cli.ts` is `0.0.0.0`, so the anonymous API is reachable off-box unless operators override it.",
          "Dashboard and collector clients in `src/dashboard/hooks/useTelemetry.ts` and `src/collector/index.ts` call the server anonymously, which confirms that session listings, raw event streams, and ingest endpoints are all currently treated as open access."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Introduce a single server-side auth layer before route registration: require an API key or signed token for collector/ingest routes, separate a read-only dashboard credential from write-capable ingestion credentials, and leave only `/api/health` explicitly unauthenticated. Apply the policy through grouped route plugins so new endpoints inherit it by default.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
