      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Low-level config loading performs unsolicited logging and silent fallback on every read",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "low_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "src/shared/config.ts",
          "src/sdk/rag.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`loadConfig()` logs successful loads with `console.log` and parse failures with `console.warn`, even though it is a shared library helper rather than a CLI entrypoint.",
          "On parse failure it returns `{}` after warning, so callers like `createRagTracersFromConfig()` quietly degrade to an empty tracer map instead of letting the caller choose how to handle bad config.",
          "Because `createRagTracersFromConfig()` calls `loadConfig()` internally, simply constructing SDK helpers can emit stdout noise and hide broken configuration."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Keep `loadConfig()` side-effect free: return `{ config, path }` or throw a typed error, and move all user-facing logging/warning decisions to CLI/server entrypoints that can choose the right behavior.",
