    "review::.::holistic::design_coherence::dashboard_visualizations_form_style_islands::16f6e430": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::design_coherence::dashboard_visualizations_form_style_islands::16f6e430",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "The dashboard\u2019s visualization layer uses incompatible styling and composition patterns, so presentation changes require many one-off edits instead of flowing through shared primitives.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "design_coherence",
        "related_files": [
          "src/dashboard/dashboard.css.ts",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/McpStatsPanel.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/RagStatsPanel.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/ActivitySparklines.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/ContextUtilizationChart.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/DriftPanel.tsx"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`src/dashboard/dashboard.css.ts` defines shared shell, panel, header, body, and event-feed styles backed by tokens, but the visualization components hardcode their own `fontFamily`, `rgba(...)` palette, spacing, and borders inline.",
          "`McpStatsPanel` and `RagStatsPanel` hand-roll nearly identical table layouts independently instead of sharing a common stats-table primitive.",
          "`DriftPanel` uses the design-system `DataGrid`, while `ActivitySparklines` and `ContextUtilizationChart` use bespoke inline-rendered widgets with unrelated color and typography conventions, creating multiple structural patterns for the same dashboard area."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Create a small shared visualization kit for this dashboard: token-backed typography/color helpers plus a reusable stats-table/panel shell. Then migrate the existing panels onto those primitives so visual changes and accessibility fixes land once.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-02T01:44:24+00:00",
