    "review::.::holistic::low_level_elegance::dashboard_session_events_reduplicated::7a3664eb": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::low_level_elegance::dashboard_session_events_reduplicated::7a3664eb",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "DashboardPage re-appends the full session event history on every websocket update",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "low_level_elegance",
        "related_files": [
          "src/dashboard/pages/DashboardPage.tsx",
          "src/dashboard/hooks/useTelemetry.ts",
          "src/dashboard/visualizations/TokenFlowChart.tsx"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`useTelemetry()` stores `events` as the rolling full websocket history in [src/dashboard/hooks/useTelemetry.ts](/Users/donovanadams/Desktop/hydrotik/packages/hy-ai-rum/src/dashboard/hooks/useTelemetry.ts).",
          "`DashboardPage` filters that whole array by `activeSessionId` and then does `setSessionEvents((prev) => [...prev, ...relevant])` whenever `events` changes, so each new event re-appends all previously relevant events in [src/dashboard/pages/DashboardPage.tsx](/Users/donovanadams/Desktop/hydrotik/packages/hy-ai-rum/src/dashboard/pages/DashboardPage.tsx).",
          "`TokenFlowChart` derives its series by filtering `sessionEvents`, so duplicated local history inflates chart rows and any other session-scoped visualization that trusts this state in [src/dashboard/visualizations/TokenFlowChart.tsx](/Users/donovanadams/Desktop/hydrotik/packages/hy-ai-rum/src/dashboard/visualizations/TokenFlowChart.tsx)."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Replace the append logic with a derivation that only adds newly seen event IDs for the active session, or stop storing `sessionEvents` separately and derive it from the fetched base plus incremental websocket deltas keyed by event ID.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-02T01:44:24+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-02T01:44:24+00:00",
